Pop a #frying pan{} on medium heat with a splash of @oil{}. Add the @spiced pork sausages{4} and cook, turning frequently to make sure they brown evenly, ~{5-7%minutes}. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(halved and thinly sliced) into half moons. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and leaves separated).

Pour the @water{200%ml} for the bulgur wheat into a large #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. Stir in half the @chicken stock powder{1}, then tip in the @bulgur wheat{100%g}. Bring back to the boil, cover with a #lid{}, remove from the heat and leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

When the sausages are browned, add the onion to the pan with the sausages. Cook, stirring occasionally, for ~{5%minutes} until softened, then stir in the garlic, @smoked paprika{1} and @ground coriander{1}. Cook for a couple of minutes until everything smells delicious and fragrant.

Add the @tomato passata{2%500ml jars} to the frying pan, bring to the boil, then stir in the remaining stock pot and the @water{200%ml} for the sauce. Reduce the heat to medium and leave to simmer until thickened and reduced by half, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, drain and rinse the @red kidney beans{1%400g can}(drained and rinsed) in a #sieve{}. Remove the roots from the @spring onions{3}(roots removed) and thinly slice. Zest and juice the @lemon{1/2}(zested and juiced). Once the sauce has reduced by half, stir in the kidney beans and @sliced spring greens{150%g}, reduce the heat to low and cook until the spring greens have wilted, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Fluff up the bulgur wheat with a #fork{} and mix in the spring onion, half the chopped coriander and enough lemon juice and zest to taste. Season with @?salt{} and @?pepper{} if you feel it needs it. Stir the remaining chopped coriander through the sausage hotpot and serve on top of a bed of bulgur wheat. Enjoy!

> It's often assumed that 'hot pot' refers to the earthenware pot used in British cuisine, but it's actually connected with the hodge-podge of ingredients within.

> Bursting with rich, fragrant spices like ground coriander and smoked paprika, and served with nutty bulgur wheat (it should retain a bit of its bite), this dish is the ultimate quick fix dinner for a mid week evening.